\title{grainsizeR: sediment grain-size analysis tools}
\description{
grainsizeR provides tools for sediment grain-size analysis in R. It reads
retained grain-size distributions, stores them as validated \code{gsd_tbl}
objects, calculates boundary-based grain-size statistics, and creates common
plots for distribution, cumulative, fraction, and ternary texture workflows.
}
\details{
Input data can be supplied in long format, with one row per sample and size
class, or in wide format, with size classes in rows and samples in columns.
Values may be retained proportions, retained percentages, or weights that
are normalized within each sample.

In grainsizeR, \code{D_p} is the grain size at which \code{p} percent of the sample is
finer. For example, \code{D50} is the median grain size on the percent-finer
curve.

A typical workflow is:
\enumerate{
\item Read data with \code{read_gsd()} or \code{read_gsd_wide()}.
\item Inspect and validate the resulting \code{gsd_tbl}.
\item Calculate D-values with \code{gs_d_values()}.
\item Calculate additional grain-size indices with
\code{gs_grain_size_indices()}.
\item Calculate Folk and Ward statistics with \code{gs_folk_ward()}.
\item Optionally calculate moments with explicit open-end handling using
\code{gs_moments()}.
\item Calculate fractions with \code{gs_fractions()} or \code{gs_fractions_wide()}.
\item Plot results with \code{plot_distribution()}, \code{plot_cumulative()},
\code{plot_fractions()}, and \code{plot_texture_ternary()}.
\item Optionally classify samples with user-supplied texture polygons.
}

Open-ended terminal classes are not silently treated as bounded intervals.
Calculations that would require values inside open tails require explicit
extrapolation or unresolved-value handling. Built-in official texture polygon
datasets are not bundled yet. The package does not implement civil
engineering classification systems.
}
